# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: BlackMonolith | Scene: TheBlackMonolithMage9
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "Sarah walks the familiar path."
    new "Sarah walks the familiar path."

    old "As a child, she ran these halls a thousand times over."
    new "As a child, she ran these halls a thousand times over."

    old "Though it has been years since she was last here, she can walk the hall by memory."
    new "Though it has been years since she was last here, she can walk the hall by memory."

    old "But only their dimensions are true."
    new "But only their dimensions are true."

    old "The halls are cold and empty. Her footsteps echo as they never did in her childhood."
    new "The halls are cold and empty. Her footsteps echo as they never did in her childhood."

    old "The throne room is like a taxidermy mount. Perfect in its imitation, yet stripped of all life. Stripped of the most essential part."
    new "The throne room is like a taxidermy mount. Perfect in its imitation, yet stripped of all life. Stripped of the most essential part."

    old "You come here more often than you did before."
    new "You come here more often than you did before."

    old "You trouble me in my waking days. Now you trouble me in my dreams as well, spirit?"
    new "You trouble me in my waking days. Now you trouble me in my dreams as well, spirit?"

    old "Should I be a trouble to you, speak the word and I will fade away."
    new "Should I be a trouble to you, speak the word and I will fade away."

    old "In her dreams, the castle was always empty. Hollow. The spirit was no real replacement for life, but it seemed more fitting than to be alone."
    new "In her dreams, the castle was always empty. Hollow. The spirit was no real replacement for life, but it seemed more fitting than to be alone."

    old "No, stay Razaphel."
    new "No, stay Razaphel."

    old "The spirit remained."
    new "The spirit remained."

    old "Sarah sat down on the throne."
    new "Sarah sat down on the throne."

    old "Do you often know you dream?"
    new "Do you often know you dream?"

    old "Sarah looked out across the illusioned hall of her youth."
    new "Sarah looked out across the illusioned hall of her youth."

    old "Sometimes. When its a familiar dream like this...more often."
    new "Sometimes. When its a familiar dream like this...more often."

    old "Is that odd?"
    new "Is that odd?"

    old "We are wise to value our dreams. But only fools waste time dissecting them."
    new "We are wise to value our dreams. But only fools waste time dissecting them."

    old "What of you, spirit? Are you real, or part of my dreams?"
    new "What of you, spirit? Are you real, or part of my dreams?"

    old "Would you dream up a creature like me?"
    new "Would you dream up a creature like me?"

    old "Sarah chuckled to herself."
    new "Sarah chuckled to herself."

    old "If I did I would certainly not have made you so annoying. So full of riddles."
    new "If I did I would certainly not have made you so annoying. So full of riddles."

    old "The spirit hissed, some odd variant of laughter."
    new "The spirit hissed, some odd variant of laughter."

    old "Sarah swore she could feel the solidness the throne against her hands, even though she knew it all to be illusion."
    new "Sarah swore she could feel the solidness the throne against her hands, even though she knew it all to be illusion."

    old "I doubt this room still looks like this. Probably home to some tribesman warlord."
    new "I doubt this room still looks like this. Probably home to some tribesman warlord."

    old "Does it anger you? Knowing your home is defiled?"
    new "Does it anger you? Knowing your home is defiled?"

    old "It used to."
    new "It used to."

    old "Whenever I would think of it, I could feel a fury in my heart."
    new "Whenever I would think of it, I could feel a fury in my heart."

    old "But over the years, it grew softer and softer. By now, I barely feel anything at all."
    new "But over the years, it grew softer and softer. By now, I barely feel anything at all."

    old "It's home...but the more I think of it, the more it feels only factually so."
    new "It's home...but the more I think of it, the more it feels only factually so."

    old "Suppose I came in here, blazing with fire. Burned a hundred or a thousand tribsmen. Then what?"
    new "Suppose I came in here, blazing with fire. Burned a hundred or a thousand tribsmen. Then what?"

    old "I have no father waiting for me. No brother."
    new "I have no father waiting for me. No brother."

    old "I could come back and sit upon a cold throne, ruling an empire of...nothing."
    new "I could come back and sit upon a cold throne, ruling an empire of...nothing."

    old "I have no dreams of ruling anything, spirit."
    new "I have no dreams of ruling anything, spirit."

    old "She watched as Razaphel drifted through the Great Hall."
    new "She watched as Razaphel drifted through the Great Hall."

    old "Yet you are more powerful than you have ever been. And you will grow more powerful still."
    new "Yet you are more powerful than you have ever been. And you will grow more powerful still."

    old "What does it all add up to?"
    new "What does it all add up to?"

    old "She threw up her hands in exasperation."
    new "She threw up her hands in exasperation."

    old "Wish I knew."
    new "Wish I knew."

    old "She saw the spirit come closer to her."
    new "She saw the spirit come closer to her."

    old "Would you like to know your Fate?"
    new "Would you like to know your Fate?"

    old "Sarah eyed the spirit."
    new "Sarah eyed the spirit."

    old "More prophecies?"
    new "More prophecies?"

    old "The word lingered for a moment."
    new "The word lingered for a moment."

    old "What war?"
    new "What war?"

    old "A great and final war draws closer."
    new "A great and final war draws closer."

    old "The war whose outcome is fixed by divine hand. A war whose outcome only you can alter."
    new "The war whose outcome is fixed by divine hand. A war whose outcome only you can alter."

    old "There has always been war in this world. There will always be another."
    new "There has always been war in this world. There will always be another."

    old "None like this."
    new "None like this."

    old "She saw the spirit expand, growing, filling the room."
    new "She saw the spirit expand, growing, filling the room."

    old "The veils between the worlds will rupture and my kind, our Horde, will sweep out across the land."
    new "The veils between the worlds will rupture and my kind, our Horde, will sweep out across the land."

    old "Millions will be put to the grave."
    new "Millions will be put to the grave."

    old "They will descend on the world like locusts and leave empires barren as fields."
    new "They will descend on the world like locusts and leave empires barren as fields."

    old "Sarah saw images in the mist of the spirit's body."
    new "Sarah saw images in the mist of the spirit's body."

    old "Corpses, piled up like mountains, the smell of rotting flesh filling up the room."
    new "Corpses, piled up like mountains, the smell of rotting flesh filling up the room."

    old "Why are you showing me this?"
    new "Why are you showing me this?"

    old "Her voice trembled at the sight."
    new "Her voice trembled at the sight."

    old "Do...do I stop this?"
    new "Do...do I stop this?"

    old "More images. More horrors."
    new "More images. More horrors."

    old "You cannot stop this, for both sides yearn for this great and calamitous war."
    new "You cannot stop this, for both sides yearn for this great and calamitous war."

    old "Sides?"
    new "Sides?"

    old "The Gods on their end. The-King-On-The-Outside on his end."
    new "The Gods on their end. The-King-On-The-Outside on his end."

    old "Sarah shivered at the names and the sight of more horrors playing out before her."
    new "Sarah shivered at the names and the sight of more horrors playing out before her."

    old "Entire cities, not a life to them."
    new "Entire cities, not a life to them."

    old "This can't be...there has to be a way to stop this..."
    new "This can't be...there has to be a way to stop this..."

    old "There is none."
    new "There is none."

    old "The veil will break and one world will pour out into another."
    new "The veil will break and one world will pour out into another."

    old "Sarah stared at the vision before her."
    new "Sarah stared at the vision before her."

    old "You say this war cannot be stopped. You say its outcome cannot be altered. Then why? Why will your race not hold back?"
    new "You say this war cannot be stopped. You say its outcome cannot be altered. Then why? Why will your race not hold back?"

    old "Silence lingered in the room for a moment."
    new "Silence lingered in the room for a moment."

    old "I have told you of my world. The infinite nature of our lives. The endless torment of our existence beneath your world."
    new "I have told you of my world. The infinite nature of our lives. The endless torment of our existence beneath your world."

    old "Sarah nodded. She knew the story well by now."
    new "Sarah nodded. She knew the story well by now."

    old "But you do not yet understand the nature of my race entirely."
    new "But you do not yet understand the nature of my race entirely."

    old "You believe us to be like you. But even there you make a profound mistake."
    new "You believe us to be like you. But even there you make a profound mistake."

    old "The torment of my race is not simply a physical torture. Trapped beneath your world, it is not only our bodies that are broken."
    new "The torment of my race is not simply a physical torture. Trapped beneath your world, it is not only our bodies that are broken."

    old "Caught in the ever tightenting press, our bodies break, but so too do our spirits. Our souls."
    new "Caught in the ever tightenting press, our bodies break, but so too do our spirits. Our souls."

    old "You imagine our race, like yours, to be one of many singulars."
    new "You imagine our race, like yours, to be one of many singulars."

    old "But over the millenia, the torture has ripped at the edges of our souls and minds, just the same as it rended our flesh."
    new "But over the millenia, the torture has ripped at the edges of our souls and minds, just the same as it rended our flesh."

    old "And where once we were seperate, we have grown over the eons to become singular."
    new "And where once we were seperate, we have grown over the eons to become singular."

    old "Sarah stared at the spirit's face-mask, forever unmoving."
    new "Sarah stared at the spirit's face-mask, forever unmoving."

    old "I first noticed this a great many centuries ago."
    new "I first noticed this a great many centuries ago."

    old "In life, I was a great scholar and mage in the world."
    new "In life, I was a great scholar and mage in the world."

    old "Trapped as I was, tortured like all the others, I sought out my comfort in my memories. Dreaming of the paradise that I once had."
    new "Trapped as I was, tortured like all the others, I sought out my comfort in my memories. Dreaming of the paradise that I once had."

    old "Again and again, I ran through the memories, the little comforts that I had."
    new "Again and again, I ran through the memories, the little comforts that I had."

    old "The spirit slipped closer."
    new "The spirit slipped closer."

    old "Until one day, I found myself reliving a memory that was not mine."
    new "Until one day, I found myself reliving a memory that was not mine."

    old "And yet, among all the other memories of my mind, I could not tell it apart."
    new "And yet, among all the other memories of my mind, I could not tell it apart."

    old "I knew it could not have been mine by sheer fact, but it did not feel false or other compared to the memories that I knew to be mine."
    new "I knew it could not have been mine by sheer fact, but it did not feel false or other compared to the memories that I knew to be mine."

    old "Over the decades, the false memories grew and grew, until I realized one day the truth of it."
    new "Over the decades, the false memories grew and grew, until I realized one day the truth of it."

    old "Sarah saw the spirit's body twist around."
    new "Sarah saw the spirit's body twist around."

    old "They were not false memories at all. They were simply the memories of others from my race. Bleeding into me."
    new "They were not false memories at all. They were simply the memories of others from my race. Bleeding into me."

    old "Slowly, who I was or had been, became infected with the minds of others. Where I ended and they began, or inverse, I could no longer tell."
    new "Slowly, who I was or had been, became infected with the minds of others. Where I ended and they began, or inverse, I could no longer tell."

    old "And I realized that my fate was not unique."
    new "And I realized that my fate was not unique."

    old "Among my race, as the torture grew and grew, our minds broke and shattered, and the remnants poured into a great swirling mass."
    new "Among my race, as the torture grew and grew, our minds broke and shattered, and the remnants poured into a great swirling mass."

    old "The great collective of our race. The horrid pool of our collective mind."
    new "The great collective of our race. The horrid pool of our collective mind."

    old "Sarah held her breath as the spirit continued."
    new "Sarah held her breath as the spirit continued."

    old "As my race converged, they became as a mob. They did not grow wiser, rather, the more pooled together, the more singular their reasoning."
    new "As my race converged, they became as a mob. They did not grow wiser, rather, the more pooled together, the more singular their reasoning."

    old "Nuance could not exist in this place, and so only simply thoughts could win out, drowning all other thought."
    new "Nuance could not exist in this place, and so only simply thoughts could win out, drowning all other thought."

    old "Differing groups formed."
    new "Differing groups formed."

    old "The greater groups ate the smaller. On and on. Until eventually, only one would remain."
    new "The greater groups ate the smaller. On and on. Until eventually, only one would remain."

    old "The-King-On-The-Outside."
    new "The-King-On-The-Outside."

    old "Realizing this inevitable fate, I knew I had to slip away before I too would be consumed."
    new "Realizing this inevitable fate, I knew I had to slip away before I too would be consumed."

    old "I tricked your mage, your Order, to capture me."
    new "I tricked your mage, your Order, to capture me."

    old "I knew their hunger for information on my race, and so I seduced them."
    new "I knew their hunger for information on my race, and so I seduced them."

    old "Fragments of my being scattered out across your world. The Fate Stones, but the greatest sliver of myself I buried hidden in the desert."
    new "Fragments of my being scattered out across your world. The Fate Stones, but the greatest sliver of myself I buried hidden in the desert."

    old "Safe from the Order. Safe from the Gods. Safe even from my own kind."
    new "Safe from the Order. Safe from the Gods. Safe even from my own kind."

    old "Sarah felt the room spin as the spirit told her all of it."
    new "Sarah felt the room spin as the spirit told her all of it."

    old "You...you're a traitor to your own race?"
    new "You...you're a traitor to your own race?"

    old "No...I ran because I knew their path led to war. And I knew their war would fail."
    new "No...I ran because I knew their path led to war. And I knew their war would fail."

    old "If their war is destined to fail, why would they wage it?"
    new "If their war is destined to fail, why would they wage it?"

    old "Because they are like a mob in every sense."
    new "Because they are like a mob in every sense."

    old "They are driven by a simple desire, to escape their horrid torture. And for a brief moment, they will. But they are lured into a trap. A war they cannot win."
    new "They are driven by a simple desire, to escape their horrid torture. And for a brief moment, they will. But they are lured into a trap. A war they cannot win."

    old "A war the Gods have forseen and whose end they expect."
    new "A war the Gods have forseen and whose end they expect."

    old "So they fight a war they know they will lose?"
    new "So they fight a war they know they will lose?"

    old "The complexity of my race has been wiped away. Only a singular impulse remains. To break free of their condition."
    new "The complexity of my race has been wiped away. Only a singular impulse remains. To break free of their condition."

    old "They will seek it out, even if they lose."
    new "They will seek it out, even if they lose."

    old "Sarah buried her face in her hands."
    new "Sarah buried her face in her hands."

    old "And you? You have snuck to escape all this?"
    new "And you? You have snuck to escape all this?"

    old "I stole myself into your world so that I might remain myself."
    new "I stole myself into your world so that I might remain myself."

    old "So that I might still conceive of ways to avert the eternal torture of my race. To give a chance for both worlds."
    new "So that I might still conceive of ways to avert the eternal torture of my race. To give a chance for both worlds."

    old "Sarah studied the spirit intently, hoping she could read anything in its body or voice."
    new "Sarah studied the spirit intently, hoping she could read anything in its body or voice."

    old "When? When will this war begin?"
    new "When? When will this war begin?"

    old "Soon."
    new "Soon."

    old "That is not an answer to my question."
    new "That is not an answer to my question."

    old "Yet it is all I can give you. I do not know the passing of every minute. I know only the broad design."
    new "Yet it is all I can give you. I do not know the passing of every minute. I know only the broad design."

    old "Sarah grew quiet, considering all that the spirit had told her."
    new "Sarah grew quiet, considering all that the spirit had told her."

    old "The images of the carnage haunted her."
    new "The images of the carnage haunted her."

    old "Could such a thing truly be inevitable?"
    new "Could such a thing truly be inevitable?"

    old "Why do you tell me all of this now?"
    new "Why do you tell me all of this now?"

    old "Because as the hour draws near, you must be ready."
    new "Because as the hour draws near, you must be ready."

    old "For all that will come. For all you will have to do. To save my world as well as your own."
    new "For all that will come. For all you will have to do. To save my world as well as your own."

    old "The spirit's words lingered."
    new "The spirit's words lingered."

    old "As the silence grew deeper, the world around her began to fade."
    new "As the silence grew deeper, the world around her began to fade."

    old "Slowly, Sarah fell out of her dream and woke to the real world."
    new "Slowly, Sarah fell out of her dream and woke to the real world."

    old "Sarah woke to her bed."
    new "Sarah woke to her bed."

    old "The cold air moved across her body, drenched in sweat."
    new "The cold air moved across her body, drenched in sweat."

    old "The world was real again."
    new "The world was real again."

    old "In her mind, the spirit's prophecy churned."
    new "In her mind, the spirit's prophecy churned."

